Mini Project 1 Problem 2: K-means Clustering¶

Name: Fei Yin¶

PID: A15555426¶

In this problem, we will build a K-means clustering algorithm to cluster the hand-written digits into a certain number of clusters. In effect, this is an unsupervised machine learning algorithm. After building the algorithm, we will test its performance on different number of clusters. Also, since the algorithm starts by randomly assigning data vectors to clusters, the clustering converges to different final states, so we will repeat each experiment multiple times.

Important Note: To speed up some processes in this part of the project, multiprocessing is used. To ensure memory leak does not happen, make sure to run jupyter notebook --NotebookApp.max_buffer_size=8589934592 in terminal to re-open Jupyter Notebook. This sets the memory limit of Jupyter Notebook to 8 GB. However, if a system's usable memory is less than 8GB, potential freeze could happen. In that case, try reducing the pool count by changing the multiprocessing_pool_count variable, located in the code cell below, to a smaller number. This is also noted in the README file.

The kmeans function below implements the K-means clustering algorithm. It initializes by randomly assigning data_vectors into K (cluster_count) clusters while also initializing other return variables. After initialization, iterations start. During each iteration, three thing happen: 1) group representative vectors (grvs) are calculated to be the centroid of each of their corresponding clusters, 2) each data vector is reassigned to the closest group representative vector, and 3) j_clust is recalculated. The iteration stops when the difference between consecutive j_clust is less than 10. The function returns the final group assignment indices (gais), the final group representative vectors (grvs), and a list of all the j_clust values after every iteration (j_clusts).

In [4]:
def kmeans(data_vectors, cluster_count):
    """Cluster the input vectors with K-means until difference between consecutive j clust is less than 10.

    Keyword arguments:
    data_vectors -- the input vectors to cluster
    cluster_count -- number of clusters to form
    
    Returns:
    gais -- group assignment indices after the final iteration
    grvs -- group representative vectors after the final iteration
    j_clusts -- a list of j_clust values after every iteration 
    """
    
    ## Seed random such that every process in multiprocessing has a different random sequence
    np.random.seed()
    
    ## Initialize by assigning each data vector to a random cluster
    gais = np.random.randint(cluster_count, size=data_vectors.shape[0])
    grvs = np.zeros((cluster_count, data_vectors.shape[1]))
    j_clusts = []
    
    j_clust_old = float(sys.maxsize)
    j_clust = float(sys.maxsize) / 2
    
    ## Terminate when J clust difference between iterations is less than 10
    while (j_clust_old - j_clust) > 10:
        
        j_clust_old = j_clust
        
        ## Assign each group representative vector its corresponding cluster's centroid
        for i in range(cluster_count):    
            grvs[i] = np.mean(data_vectors[gais == i], axis=0)
        
        ## Assign each data vector to the cluster with the closest group representative vector
        for i, data_vector in enumerate(data_vectors):
            min_distance = float('inf')
            closest_cluster_index = 0
            
            for j, grv in enumerate(grvs):
                distance = np.subtract(data_vector, grv).T @ np.subtract(data_vector, grv)
                
                if distance < min_distance:
                    min_distance = distance
                    closest_cluster_index = j
                    
            gais[i] = closest_cluster_index
            j_clust += min_distance
                
        ## Calculate J clust
        j_clust /= data_vectors.shape[0]
        j_clusts.append(j_clust)
        #print('j_clust difference: ', j_clust_old - j_clust)
    
    #print('kmeans run completed')
    return gais, grvs, j_clusts
In [5]:
def findMinMaxJclustIndices(clustering_results):
    """Find the indices of the two runs resulting in the largest and smallest j_clust upon convergence.

    Keyword arguments:
    clustering_results -- a list of clustering results
                          Each clustering result is a tuple of gais, grvs, and j_clusts.
                          Details of these three variables can be found in the docstring of the kmeans function.
    
    Returns:
    max_j_clust_index -- index of the run resulting in the largest j_clust upon convergence
    min_j_clust_index -- index of the run resulting in the smallest j_clust upon convergence 
    """
    
    max_j_clust = 0.0 
    min_j_clust = float(sys.maxsize)
    max_j_clust_index = 0
    min_j_clust_index = 0

    for i, result in enumerate(clustering_results):
        if result[2][-1] > max_j_clust:
            max_j_clust = result[2][-1]
            max_j_clust_index = i
        if result[2][-1] < min_j_clust:
            min_j_clust = result[2][-1]
            min_j_clust_index = i
        
    return max_j_clust_index, min_j_clust_index
In [51]:
def findTenNearest(data_vectors, grv):
    """Find 10 nearest data vectors with repect to the group representative vector given.
    
    Keyword arguments:
    data_vectors -- a set of input vectors
    grv -- a group representative vector
    
    Returns:
    ten_nearest_vectors -- 10 data vectors that are nearest to the group representative vector 
    """
    
    ten_nearest_vectors = np.zeros((10, data_vectors.shape[1]))
    ten_nearest_distances = np.ones((10, 1)) * np.inf 
    
    for data_vector in data_vectors:        
        distance = np.subtract(data_vector, grv).T @ np.subtract(data_vector, grv)
        
        for i in range(10):
            if distance < ten_nearest_distances[i]:
                ten_nearest_distances[i] = distance
                ten_nearest_vectors[i] = data_vector
                break
                
    return ten_nearest_vectors
In [7]:
## istarmap function comes from:
##   https://stackoverflow.com/questions/57354700/starmap-combined-with-tqdm
def istarmap(self, func, iterable, chunksize=1):
    """starmap-version of imap"""
    
    if self._state != mpp.RUN:
        raise ValueError("Pool not running")

    if chunksize < 1:
        raise ValueError(
            "Chunksize must be 1+, not {0:n}".format(
                chunksize))

    task_batches = mpp.Pool._get_tasks(func, iterable, chunksize)
    result = mpp.IMapIterator(self._cache)
    self._taskqueue.put(
        (
            self._guarded_task_generation(result._job,
                                          mpp.starmapstar,
                                          task_batches),
            result._set_length
        ))
    return (item for chunk in result for item in chunk)

mpp.Pool.istarmap = istarmap

Test 1: K = 20, P = 30¶

For the first test, kmeans is run 30 times, where each run clusters the data vectors into 20 clusters.

In [11]:
K = 20
P = 30

## Code for tracking time consumption comes from:
##   https://stackoverflow.com/questions/1557571/how-do-i-get-time-of-a-python-programs-execution
start_time = time.time()
t1_results = []

## Code for using tqdm with istarmap comes from:
##   https://stackoverflow.com/questions/57354700/starmap-combined-with-tqdm
with mpp.Pool(multiprocessing_pool_count) as pool:
    arguments = [(train_x, K) for i in range(P)]
    for result in tqdm.tqdm(pool.istarmap(kmeans, arguments), total=len(arguments)):
        t1_results.append(result)
    
print("--- %s seconds ---" % (time.time() - start_time))

The plot above shows the two sets of j_clusts as a function of number of iterations. The last j_clust in each of the two sets of j_clusts corresponds to the largest and smallest j_clust values upon convergence. The difference between those values can clearly be seen on the plot. Within my multiple trials, I have seen the two curves taking slightly different shapes. For example, one curve could end earlier than another, or the two curves could cross path at some point. However, the variations in their paths do not seem to be directly related to their final values. And, reasonably, all of the j_clusts vs. number of iterations curves roughly follow logarithmic decaying paths.

10 nearest data points to each of the K group representatives¶
To evaluate the performance of kmeans, we want to understand how well each group representative represents its cluster. To do that, we pick 10 nearest data vectors around each group representative and manually record whether they are misclassified or not.


To conveniently compare each group representative with the 10 nearest data vectors around it, we display them as images side by side, creating an image grid. We distinguish group representatives from data vectors by setting the group representatives to red-scale and the data vectors to gray-scale.


In an image grid, each row starts with a group representative on the left, followed by 10 nearest data vectors around it. Below each image grid, a table mimicking the format of the image grid is manually created. To record the number of misclassified images for each group representative, one more column is added to the table.


Since we have 20 group representatives representing 20 clusters here, we pick 200 data vectors for the maximum j_clust case and 200 data vectors for the minimum j_clust case.

From the table above, we can calculate the error rate of the K = 20 run with the smallest j_clust upon convergence to be (6 + 8 + 7 + 1 + 2) / 200 = 12%. The error rate of this run is higher than that of the run with the largest j_clust upon convergence, which is counter-intuitive. However, this can be explained if we account for the subjective aspect involved in calculating the error rate. That is, in calculating the error rate, the digits that the group representatives represent are determined by me based on what I know about digits. However, what I know about digits is not involved in the program's learning process. So its interpretation of the group representatives can be different from my knowledge. For example, for the 9th row, I think the group representative is "9", but 8 of the 10 closest data vectors are "4". So the program might have learned that some of what I see as "9" are actually closer to "4".

Test 3: K = 5, P = 10¶
For the third test, kmeans is run 10 times, where each run clusters the data vectors into 5 clusters.











In [35]:



     


K = 5
P = 10
start_time = time.time()
t3_results = []

with mpp.Pool(multiprocessing_pool_count) as pool:
    arguments = [(train_x, K) for i in range(P)]
    for result in tqdm.tqdm(pool.istarmap(kmeans, arguments), total=len(arguments)):
        t3_results.append(result)
    
print("--- %s seconds ---" % (time.time() - start_time))

10 nearest data points to each of the K group representatives¶
To evaluate the performance of kmeans, we want to understand how well each group representative represents its cluster. To do that, we pick 10 nearest data vectors around each group representative and manually record whether they are misclassified or not.


To conveniently compare each group representative with the 10 nearest data vectors around it, we display them as images side by side, creating an image grid. We distinguish group representatives from data vectors by setting the group representatives to red-scale and the data vectors to gray-scale.


In an image grid, each row starts with a group representative on the left, followed by 10 nearest data vectors around it. Below each image grid, a table mimicking the format of the image grid is manually created. To record the number of misclassified images for each group representative, one more column is added to the table.


Since we have 5 group representatives representing 5 clusters here, we pick 50 data vectors for the maximum j_clust case and 50 data vectors for the minimum j_clust case.

Comparing K-means Clustering with Least Squares Classifiers¶










The two Least Squares Classifiers produced about 7% and 14% error rates, respectively, on both the training set and testing set, producing consistent performance. The error rates of the K-means algorithm vary for different number of clusters as well as different trials, which means its performance is not as consistent. Also, the K-means algorithm takes significantly longer time to run. However, because the two Least Squares Classifiers are supervised algorithms whereas K-means is unsupervised, comparing their error rates alone does not seem to tell the full story. To elaborate:


1) Least Squares Classifiers are trained on a set of features with corresponding labels. That is, answers are provided during their learning processes. So, during testing, if the answers follow the same logic, then their performance would be consistent. Also, they could be trained on a certain set of features and labels then be applied to a different set, such ability to generalize is not found on K-means.


2) K-means, on the other hand, is trained on a set of features with no labels. That is, no answers are provided during its learning process. It has to discover the answers that it thinks as the most reasonable. Those answers might deviate from the labels that are hidden from it, in which case the performance would take a hit. However, if the problem itself does not come with answers, then K-means is a good way to help find potential answers whereas Least Squares Classifiers would not know what to do if answers are not provided during the training process.


To summarize, if labels exist for the features, then Least Squares Classifiers are fast, consistent, and generalizable, whereas K-means is slow, inconsistent, and not generalizable. On the other hand, if labels do not exist for the features, then Least Squares Classifiers are not applicable, whereas K-means is able to find potential answers.
